00:14:00.160 --> 00:14:01.460
But...

00:14:01.460 --> 00:14:02.760
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: Does it work?

00:14:02.760 --> 00:14:04.060
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
Hasn't worked yet,

00:14:04.060 --> 00:14:05.360
but hope is, hope springs eternal.

00:14:05.360 --> 00:14:09.010
So, let me ask you, you have
interviewed Donald Trump.

00:14:09.010 --> 00:14:10.310
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: Yes.

00:14:10.310 --> 00:14:11.610
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:

00:14:11.610 --> 00:14:12.910
Any impressions you
would like to convey?

00:14:12.910 --> 00:14:14.600
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: This
was five months ago.

00:14:14.600 --> 00:14:21.240
Bob Costa, reporter at the Post,
and I interviewed him, and,

00:14:21.240 --> 00:14:25.630
first of all, he wanted to
kind of do this on the phone,

00:14:25.630 --> 00:14:28.280
and we said no, we
want do it in person.

00:14:28.280 --> 00:14:34.490
I've never really met anyone
who has the capacity to measure,

00:14:34.490 --> 00:14:40.470
in the moment, the reaction he's
generating among the people he's

00:14:40.470 --> 00:14:41.770
talking to.

00:14:41.770 --> 00:14:43.810
Other words, the reaction
to himself.

00:14:43.810 --> 00:14:50.220
And so, he's, face-to-face, very
careful, not hostile, not angry.

00:14:50.220 --> 00:14:57.210
But in the text of the interview,
he said some things that, I mean,

00:14:57.210 --> 00:15:00.850
let me confess I thought
afterwards, you know,

00:15:00.850 --> 00:15:07.620
maybe that these things are
so raw that it will hurt him

00:15:07.620 --> 00:15:12.070
or maybe finish him, because one,
one of the things he said was,

00:15:12.070 --> 00:15:16.300
"I bring out rage in people."

00:15:16.300 --> 00:15:18.520
And he said that with pride.

00:15:18.520 --> 00:15:24.020
Now, I mean, you worked for
Jimmy Carter and, you know, you,

00:15:24.020 --> 00:15:26.440
Presidents have to
bring people together.

00:15:26.440 --> 00:15:31.970
Camp David Accords was an example
of, you, you can't be President

00:15:31.970 --> 00:15:35.180
and bring out rage in
people, but he does,

00:15:35.180 --> 00:15:36.960
and he thinks it's a good thing.

00:15:36.960 --> 00:15:42.900
We asked him about the economy, and
he said he thought we were going

00:15:42.900 --> 00:15:46.960
to have an awful recession.

00:15:46.960 --> 00:15:56.090
Asked him about Lincoln and
Nixon, two Republicans, and why,

00:15:56.090 --> 00:16:01.130
we asked him, why did
Lincoln succeed as President?

00:16:01.130 --> 00:16:05.760
And he went, gave a long
rambling answer, and said, well,

00:16:05.760 --> 00:16:12.970
Lincoln succeeded because he did
things that needed to be done.

00:16:12.970 --> 00:16:14.600
Now, if you were in high school,

00:16:14.600 --> 00:16:17.640
and you wrote that on
an exam [laughter]...

00:16:19.550 --> 00:16:21.300
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: So...

00:16:21.300 --> 00:16:23.750
[ Applause ]

00:16:23.750 --> 00:16:25.050
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: I mean, look.

00:16:25.050 --> 00:16:30.430
I mean, that's, he did things
that needed to be done.

00:16:30.430 --> 00:16:31.730
Like what?

00:16:31.730 --> 00:16:35.380
I get, we didn't, we were I think
embarrassed to ask [laughter].

00:16:35.380 --> 00:16:38.340
And so why did Nixon fail?

00:16:38.340 --> 00:16:41.690
And he went on a little bit,
and he said, well, basically,

00:16:41.690 --> 00:16:45.240
because of his personality
[laughter].

00:16:45.240 --> 00:16:49.100
And we couldn't, I'm sorry, I
couldn't help but say but yeah,

00:16:49.100 --> 00:16:51.650
but he was a criminal [laughter].

00:16:51.650 --> 00:16:54.850
And, and Trump said, "Oh,
that too" [laughter].

00:16:54.850 --> 00:16:56.790
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: So, now,

00:16:56.790 --> 00:16:58.800
have you interviewed
Hillary Clinton lately?

00:16:58.800 --> 00:17:00.100
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: No.

00:17:00.100 --> 00:17:03.790
She, I'm, on not the
Christmas card list.

00:17:03.790 --> 00:17:05.090
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:

00:17:05.090 --> 00:17:07.420
So she won't...but you've
interviewed her in previous times?

00:17:07.420 --> 00:17:08.720
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: Yes.

00:17:08.720 --> 00:17:10.020
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
And your impression?

00:17:10.020 --> 00:17:11.520
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: And my
impression is, I interviewed her

00:17:11.520 --> 00:17:16.690
when she was First Lady, and
she was so open and candid

00:17:16.690 --> 00:17:22.630
in describing how her husband
decided to run for President.

00:17:22.630 --> 00:17:26.460
I asked how, and she
said, oh, I know.

00:17:26.460 --> 00:17:31.950
And explained how was her idea
that he run for President.

00:17:31.950 --> 00:17:38.090
And, I, I was astonished that she
would take the credit for this,

00:17:38.090 --> 00:17:42.220
but it, we checked, and it's true.

00:17:42.220 --> 00:17:46.830
She was the one who said,
in 1991, to him, "This,

00:17:46.830 --> 00:17:50.140 position:56%
if you run, this will be your time."

00:17:50.140 --> 00:17:54.690
And he said, "Oh, no, it'll be
a dry run," and she said, "No,

00:17:54.690 --> 00:17:57.840
you will win, but you're,
it's going to be hard

00:17:57.840 --> 00:18:00.430
because the Republicans are
going to come after you,"

00:18:00.430 --> 00:18:05.570 position:56%
and there will be what she called a
"pain threshold" that we have to go,

00:18:05.570 --> 00:18:08.610
we're going to have to
go through, and over.

00:18:08.610 --> 00:18:15.570
And, and I've seen her before,
and she is a different person.

00:18:15.570 --> 00:18:20.320
I mean, whether it's that, I mean,
you know, is she different in

00:18:20.320 --> 00:18:23.070
and what we see on television,
from what you have seen?

00:18:23.070 --> 00:18:24.490
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: I'm
going to ask the questions,

00:18:24.490 --> 00:18:27.380
because people want to hear
your opinion [laughter].

00:18:27.380 --> 00:18:29.920
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: No, I asked that
question, and let it be noted

00:18:29.920 --> 00:18:31.690
that you didn't answer [laughter].

00:18:31.690 --> 00:18:34.040
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
I think people want

00:18:34.040 --> 00:18:35.570
to hear your views
on things, not mine.

00:18:35.570 --> 00:18:38.040
But let me start back.

00:18:38.040 --> 00:18:42.400
You come from a family in the
Midwest, your father was a judge.

00:18:42.400 --> 00:18:45.580
Many people who are
judges would probably

00:18:45.580 --> 00:18:48.910
like to have their children
be lawyers, too, maybe judges.

00:18:48.910 --> 00:18:50.210
You went to Yale.

00:18:50.210 --> 00:18:52.860
School that probably
produces more lawyers

00:18:52.860 --> 00:18:54.900
and business people
than journalists.

00:18:54.900 --> 00:18:57.390
Did you know you wanted to be a
journalist when you went to Yale?

00:18:57.390 --> 00:18:58.690
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: No.

00:18:58.690 --> 00:19:03.920 position:56%
And I served in the Navy five years
after college, and I was going to go

00:19:03.920 --> 00:19:08.830
to law school, and I thought,
"Oh my God, I'll be, you know,

00:19:08.830 --> 00:19:12.630
30 years old when I
get out of law school.

00:19:12.630 --> 00:19:15.310
That's the end of life [laughter].

00:19:16.400 --> 00:19:21.400
And so, I went into, to
journalism, and I told my father,

00:19:21.400 --> 00:19:26.090 position:56%
"I've got a job at this weekly paper
in Montgomery County, Maryland,

00:19:26.090 --> 00:19:29.850
that pays 115 dollars a
week, and I'm going to do

00:19:29.850 --> 00:19:31.550
that instead of going
to law school."

00:19:31.550 --> 00:19:35.090
My father, who was a
really open-minded person

00:19:35.090 --> 00:19:41.720
who didn't make judgments,
said, "You're crazy."

00:19:41.720 --> 00:19:43.600
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: So,
you did that for a while,

00:19:43.600 --> 00:19:46.150
and then you got a little bit of
a tryout with the Washington Post.

00:19:46.150 --> 00:19:47.640
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: Which I failed.

00:19:47.640 --> 00:19:49.770
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: So you
had two weeks or something, or...

00:19:49.770 --> 00:19:54.310 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: Yeah, two-week
tryout, and I wrote lots of stories,

00:19:54.310 --> 00:19:57.620
none of which they published,
and they said, you know, see,

00:19:57.620 --> 00:20:00.820
you don't know how to
do this, which is true.

00:20:00.820 --> 00:20:03.240
And, and so I worked at the...

00:20:03.240 --> 00:20:04.540
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: Okay.

00:20:04.540 --> 00:20:05.840
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: Montgomery
[inaudible].

00:20:05.840 --> 00:20:07.140
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
You worked in Montgomery,

00:20:07.140 --> 00:20:08.440
and eventually the Post
gave you another chance,

00:20:08.440 --> 00:20:10.290
and you went back, and
that was 1971, or 2.

00:20:10.290 --> 00:20:11.590
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: Yes, yes.

00:20:11.590 --> 00:20:12.890
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: '71.

00:20:12.890 --> 00:20:14.190
So, when you get back
there, and you're assigned

00:20:14.190 --> 00:20:15.490
to the metropolitan area?

00:20:15.490 --> 00:20:17.180
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: Right,
to the night police beat.

00:20:17.180 --> 00:20:18.480
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: Right.

00:20:18.480 --> 00:20:20.610
So, which is not usually a
way to advance your career,

00:20:20.610 --> 00:20:22.510
right, the night police beat?

00:20:22.510 --> 00:20:26.360
So, how did it actually happen
that you, as opposed to any

00:20:26.360 --> 00:20:31.760 position:56%
of the other 500 reporters there,
were assigned to Watergate break-in?

00:20:31.760 --> 00:20:33.770
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: I'd
been there nine months.

00:20:33.770 --> 00:20:35.700
I really loved it.

00:20:35.700 --> 00:20:39.970
I did the night police beat,
I would come in during the day

00:20:39.970 --> 00:20:45.200
and do stories, do follow-up
stories, and you can't,

00:20:45.200 --> 00:20:49.600
I can't really capture for you
completely, being in the Navy

00:20:49.600 --> 00:20:54.620
where it's controlled,
where you have no freedom.

00:20:54.620 --> 00:20:58.850
The Washington Post, at that
time, and I think now, you know,

00:20:58.850 --> 00:21:02.950
it's a reporter's newspaper, and
if you can find out something

00:21:02.950 --> 00:21:08.850
and do something, you, you're
supported by the editors.

00:21:08.850 --> 00:21:15.060 position:56%
And so, the morning of the Watergate
burglary was this Saturday morning,

00:21:15.060 --> 00:21:20.170
June 17, '72 was one of the
nicest days in Washington, by far,

00:21:20.170 --> 00:21:23.480
and the editors met,
they, this burglary was,

00:21:23.480 --> 00:21:27.680
looked like a police story, and
they said, who would be dumb enough

00:21:27.680 --> 00:21:30.790
to come in and work this morning?

00:21:30.790 --> 00:21:33.950
And immediately my name
came up [laughter].

00:21:33.950 --> 00:21:35.260
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
They called you to come in?

00:21:35.260 --> 00:21:37.420
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: Yeah, and
they called me to come in,

00:21:37.420 --> 00:21:40.770
and I went to the arraignment,
and the judge,

00:21:40.770 --> 00:21:45.020
and here are the five
burglars in business suits.

00:21:45.020 --> 00:21:49.900 position:56%
Now, I'd covered the police beat
for nine months, and I'd never heard

00:21:49.900 --> 00:21:54.540
of a burglar with a business suit
[laughter], let alone five of them,

00:21:54.540 --> 00:22:00.540
and they stood there, and
the judge asked the head,

00:22:00.540 --> 00:22:03.190
James McCord, where did you work?

00:22:03.190 --> 00:22:05.200
And McCord went, [whispered] "CIA."

00:22:05.200 --> 00:22:06.530
And the Judge said, "Speak up."

00:22:06.530 --> 00:22:08.960 position:56%
And he said, [louder whisper] "CIA."

00:22:08.960 --> 00:22:10.410
And the Judge said, "Speak up."

00:22:10.410 --> 00:22:14.900
And he said, "CIA," and I
was sitting in the front row

00:22:14.900 --> 00:22:18.610
and I think I said
out loud, "Holy shit!"

00:22:18.610 --> 00:22:22.130
[ Laughter ]

00:22:22.130 --> 00:22:23.940
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: Did
the judge hear you say that?

00:22:23.940 --> 00:22:28.610
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: No, I don't think
he did but, and, and, you know,

00:22:28.610 --> 00:22:32.600
this, and it turned out this guy
was Head of Security at the CIA,

00:22:32.600 --> 00:22:35.530
the Head of Security of the
Nixon Reelection Committee.

00:22:35.530 --> 00:22:36.830
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
But at that point,

00:22:36.830 --> 00:22:38.130
you didn't think this was a story

00:22:38.130 --> 00:22:40.580
that would really touch
Nixon, I assume.

00:22:40.580 --> 00:22:42.590
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: Yeah,
you just, you never knew.

00:22:42.590 --> 00:22:44.560
Bernstein knew.

00:22:44.560 --> 00:22:49.000
He had a nose for it, that
quite frankly, I didn't.

00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:51.300
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: So,
you began to develop the story,

00:22:51.300 --> 00:22:54.520
but for many months, people were
skeptical this was anything more

00:22:54.520 --> 00:22:58.670
than a break-in by some,
you know, rogues, let's say,

00:22:58.670 --> 00:23:00.090
and nobody thought, really,

00:23:00.090 --> 00:23:03.040
that it was Nixon behind
it, is that correct?

00:23:03.040 --> 00:23:04.360
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: Other than Carl.

00:23:04.360 --> 00:23:05.660
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: Okay.

00:23:05.660 --> 00:23:11.060 position:56%
So, but, you began to go do a lot of
research, and you published stories,

00:23:11.060 --> 00:23:15.250
many of them were used stories
that were, there were cited sources

00:23:15.250 --> 00:23:16.700
that wouldn't, you
couldn't disclose.

00:23:16.700 --> 00:23:19.670
Was that a novel thing at
the time, the, to not be able

00:23:19.670 --> 00:23:21.710
to disclose those sources?

00:23:21.710 --> 00:23:23.960
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: It
happened a lot in diplomatic

00:23:23.960 --> 00:23:30.700
and political reporting, but we
instituted a two-source rule, and,

00:23:30.700 --> 00:23:38.290
but at the same time, as you look
back on this, it was very risky,

00:23:38.290 --> 00:23:40.650
not for Carl and myself,
we were young.

00:23:40.650 --> 00:23:43.440
I could have maybe
still gone to law school

00:23:43.440 --> 00:23:46.910
if it'd turned out not to be true.

00:23:46.910 --> 00:23:51.950
And, but the risk was
borne by the editors,

00:23:51.950 --> 00:23:56.210
and particularly Ben Bradley,
and the owner, Catherine Graham.

00:23:56.210 --> 00:23:58.340
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: So, when
you began to write some stories

00:23:58.340 --> 00:23:59.870
that turned out not to be accurate,

00:23:59.870 --> 00:24:02.960
and was proven they weren't
accurate, did you get in trouble?

00:24:02.960 --> 00:24:05.420
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: Yeah, well
we got, we made some mistakes,

00:24:05.420 --> 00:24:09.020
but they were mistakes in form.

00:24:09.020 --> 00:24:14.110 position:56%
Actually, the, if you looked at the
coverage, the stories as people had,

00:24:14.110 --> 00:24:16.980
they were very conservative,
and careful,

00:24:16.980 --> 00:24:20.340
and unintentionally understated.

00:24:20.340 --> 00:24:22.750
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: So, where
were the other major newspapers?

00:24:22.750 --> 00:24:25.740 position:56%
I mean, you and Carl Bernstein get a
lot of credit, maybe all the credit,

00:24:25.740 --> 00:24:28.580 position:56%
for breaking this story, but where
were all the other major newspapers,

00:24:28.580 --> 00:24:29.880
what were they doing?

00:24:29.880 --> 00:24:31.510
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: Well,
it was a police story.

00:24:31.510 --> 00:24:36.340
You had to go, and, and, quite
frankly, it was Carl Bernstein

00:24:36.340 --> 00:24:38.450
who had the, "Well,
these people won't talk,

00:24:38.450 --> 00:24:41.770
so we have to go see them at
home, and knock on their doors,

00:24:41.770 --> 00:24:46.180
and that's what, what we did, and
we got clues, and we had Mark Felt,

00:24:46.180 --> 00:24:49.450
who was Deep Throat, the
number two in the FBI,

00:24:49.450 --> 00:24:57.220 position:56%
guiding us in a very secret way, and
we kept finding pieces of the puzzle

00:24:57.220 --> 00:24:58.520
that said, "No, wait a minute.

00:24:58.520 --> 00:25:00.860
Watergate isn't just one thing.

00:25:00.860 --> 00:25:03.800
It's a series of sabotage

00:25:03.800 --> 00:25:07.430
and espionage operations
launched by Nixon."

00:25:07.430 --> 00:25:08.730
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
Now, in the movie,

00:25:08.730 --> 00:25:10.800
there's a famous thing
about Deep Throat.

00:25:10.800 --> 00:25:12.780
And where that name
come from, by the way?

00:25:12.780 --> 00:25:16.370
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: The Managing
Editor of the Post, Howard Simons,

00:25:16.370 --> 00:25:20.980
if it was on deep background,
and so, Howard says, "Oh yeah,

00:25:20.980 --> 00:25:25.390
your guy 'Deep Throat, '" and
so the name stayed around.

00:25:25.390 --> 00:25:26.940
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
So, did you actually go

00:25:26.940 --> 00:25:28.700
into the garage and all that?

00:25:28.700 --> 00:25:30.000
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: Yeah.

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:31.300
Exactly as...

00:25:31.300 --> 00:25:32.600
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
And he was not worried

00:25:32.600 --> 00:25:34.190
that you would disclose his name?

00:25:34.190 --> 00:25:35.680
Obviously not, I guess, but...

00:25:35.680 --> 00:25:39.920 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: I think he probably
was worried but I, you know,

00:25:39.920 --> 00:25:44.100
we'd made an agreement, you
know, you make those agreements

00:25:44.100 --> 00:25:46.390
with somebody and try
to stick to them.

00:25:46.390 --> 00:25:49.140
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: So, Mark
Felt, who was the Deputy Head

00:25:49.140 --> 00:25:51.510
of the FBI, but wanted to be
the head of the FBI, presumed,

00:25:51.510 --> 00:25:54.040
what was his reason
for talking to you?

00:25:54.040 --> 00:25:58.200
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: Complicated,
like all human motivation.

00:25:58.200 --> 00:26:03.840
Some high road, some high
purpose, that this was too corrupt,

00:26:03.840 --> 00:26:06.230
and at the same time,
he was very upset

00:26:06.230 --> 00:26:10.000
that he did not get
selected to be FBI Director.

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:14.020
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
So, most people, let's say,

00:26:14.020 --> 00:26:18.070
were playing the parlor game for
20 or 30 years, Who is Deep Throat?

00:26:18.070 --> 00:26:20.150
So, when people would come
up to you and say well,

00:26:20.150 --> 00:26:22.060
can you just tell me
privately who it is,

00:26:22.060 --> 00:26:23.360
I'll just, I won't tell anybody?

00:26:23.360 --> 00:26:26.380
Did that happen a lot, and
did people get accused of it,

00:26:26.380 --> 00:26:29.000
and they were being accused of
it, and you knew they weren't it,

00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:30.570
but how did you handle all that?

00:26:30.570 --> 00:26:33.690
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: Sometimes, couple
of people were accused and said,

00:26:33.690 --> 00:26:36.730
you know, I can't get a
job unless you call the guy

00:26:36.730 --> 00:26:38.900
and say it wasn't me.

00:26:38.900 --> 00:26:46.330
And but, you know, it was, I mean,
we agreed, and I told my wife,

00:26:46.330 --> 00:26:54.010
and Bradley knew, and it, I mean, I
hate to be so practical about this,

00:26:54.010 --> 00:26:58.710
but when there was this parlor
game, and I'd go interview people,

00:26:58.710 --> 00:27:03.880
and I remember going to see a
Senator about a sensitive subject,

00:27:03.880 --> 00:27:08.500
