the record" means, again...

00:38:59.140 --> 00:39:00.490
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: You can't use it.

00:39:00.490 --> 00:39:01.810
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
You can't use it any time.

00:39:01.810 --> 00:39:05.330
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: Well, except it
doesn't mean you can't find it

00:39:05.330 --> 00:39:08.430
out elsewhere, and because
you can't, you know,

00:39:08.430 --> 00:39:11.580
flush it out of your
mind, and so sometimes,

00:39:11.580 --> 00:39:15.620
people think off the record means
it's, I'm never going to see this

00:39:15.620 --> 00:39:19.630
in print, and they're shocked when
they do, and you have to explain,

00:39:19.630 --> 00:39:23.450
yeah, you told me about this, but
I found out from somebody else,

00:39:23.450 --> 00:39:26.410
and then you want to find out more.

00:39:26.410 --> 00:39:28.310
So they know, okay, you got it...

00:39:28.310 --> 00:39:29.640
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
And that's off the record.

00:39:29.640 --> 00:39:31.270
What is background?

00:39:31.270 --> 00:39:34.390
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: Background
means that you're going to use it

00:39:34.390 --> 00:39:37.590
and not say where it came from.

00:39:37.590 --> 00:39:38.890
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
What's deep background?

00:39:38.890 --> 00:39:41.540
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: Means you're
really going to just kind of say it

00:39:41.540 --> 00:39:43.360
like it came out of the air.

00:39:43.360 --> 00:39:46.850 position:56%
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: Okay, and on
the record means that they can clean

00:39:46.850 --> 00:39:48.990
up the quotes, or they
