00:39:48.990 --> 00:39:50.290
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: No, it means,

00:39:50.290 --> 00:39:52.150
it's on the record,
you're going to use it.

00:39:52.150 --> 00:39:55.990
Sometimes people want to
go, want you to come back.

00:39:55.990 --> 00:39:59.520
I'm not really in love
with that process,

00:39:59.520 --> 00:40:03.630
because you then get people
wandering and cleaning up,

00:40:03.630 --> 00:40:08.360
and you want what they
really said and meant.

00:40:08.360 --> 00:40:09.820
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: So
when you interview somebody,

00:40:09.820 --> 00:40:12.360
do you write notes, or do you tape?

00:40:12.360 --> 00:40:16.530
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: I tape as much as
I can with the person's knowledge,

00:40:16.530 --> 00:40:19.460
and it's amazing how
all of a sudden,

00:40:19.460 --> 00:40:23.090
that tape recorder goes away, you
would think it would cause people

00:40:23.090 --> 00:40:27.430
to freeze up, but it doesn't,
because they know, okay,

00:40:27.430 --> 00:40:31.550
I'm not going to give that, I mean,
I've got transcripts of interviews

00:40:31.550 --> 00:40:39.740
from people over decades that I've
used in books, and if you look

00:40:39.740 --> 00:40:43.300
at these or listened, you
might really be surprised

00:40:43.300 --> 00:40:48.500
at the clarity and
the, forthrightness.

00:40:48.500 --> 00:40:49.800
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
When you're taping somebody,

00:40:49.800 --> 00:40:51.810
do you ever make the mistake I
do, you push the wrong button

00:40:51.810 --> 00:40:54.760
and it doesn't, the tape doesn't
work, or does it always work?

00:40:54.760 --> 00:40:56.650
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: Yeah,
