00:40:56.650 --> 00:41:00.250
The tape ran, the battery ran out.

00:41:00.250 --> 00:41:01.550
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
Now, you've interviewed,

00:41:01.550 --> 00:41:03.480
you never interviewed Nixon.

00:41:03.480 --> 00:41:04.780
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: No.

00:41:04.780 --> 00:41:06.080
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: But you
did interview President Ford?

00:41:06.080 --> 00:41:07.380
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: Yes.

00:41:07.380 --> 00:41:08.680
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: What was
your impression of President Ford?

00:41:08.680 --> 00:41:09.980
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: You know,
Gerald Ford turned out,

00:41:09.980 --> 00:41:16.910
I thought when he went, September
1974, he'd been President

00:41:16.910 --> 00:41:21.560 position:56%
for one month, went on TV
announcing, he, on a Sunday morning,

00:41:21.560 --> 00:41:27.320
giving Nixon a full pardon for
Watergate, I didn't see that.

00:41:27.320 --> 00:41:31.430
I was asleep that morning, and
Carl Bernstein called me up,

00:41:31.430 --> 00:41:33.150
and said, "Have you heard?"

00:41:33.150 --> 00:41:36.320
And I said, "I haven't heard
anything, I was asleep," and Carl,

00:41:36.320 --> 00:41:42.890 position:56%
truly the ability to say things with
the fewest words and the most drama,

00:41:42.890 --> 00:41:47.310
said, "The son of a bitch
pardoned the son of a bitch."

00:41:50.260 --> 00:41:51.560
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
[laughter] Okay.

00:41:51.560 --> 00:41:52.860
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: And
even I was able to figure

00:41:52.860 --> 00:41:54.370
out what had happened [laughter].

00:41:54.370 --> 00:41:58.420
And I thought, ah, it's the
perfect corruption, of, you know,

00:41:58.420 --> 00:42:03.890
Nixon's the one behind all
this, he gets a pardon.

00:42:03.890 --> 00:42:07.460
There was an aroma of a deal,
I later for the book "Shadow,"

00:42:07.460 --> 00:42:11.960
25 years later, met Ford and
interviewed him for the first time.

00:42:11.960 --> 00:42:19.320
Kept going back to him, and
he really explained what,

00:42:19.320 --> 00:42:24.370
what happened, and
what is important is I,

00:42:24.370 --> 00:42:28.990
I think what Ford did was really
courageous rather than corrupt.

00:42:28.990 --> 00:42:32.220
He had to move on beyond Watergate.

00:42:32.220 --> 00:42:36.130
The only way to do it was pardon
Nixon, because Nixon was going

00:42:36.130 --> 00:42:40.240
to be investigated, certainly
charged, might go to trial,

00:42:40.240 --> 00:42:43.230
might go to jail, and as
Ford said, we'd have two

00:42:43.230 --> 00:42:45.660
or three more years of Watergate.

00:42:45.660 --> 00:42:47.350
The country couldn't stand it.

00:42:47.350 --> 00:42:50.470
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: You
think had he not pardoned Nixon,

00:42:50.470 --> 00:42:51.860
he would've been reelected?

00:42:51.860 --> 00:42:53.540
Or elected?

00:42:53.540 --> 00:42:55.040
&gt;&gt; Bob Woodward: Ford?

00:42:55.040 --> 00:42:59.600 position:56%
You know, I don't, I mean, obviously
that's, if history, you don't know

00:42:59.600 --> 00:43:04.520
but Ford, in having the luxury
of time, I could go visit him

00:43:04.520 --> 00:43:08.090
at his home in Colorado,
or in California,

00:43:08.090 --> 00:43:13.420
and I think we peeled the onion
on that pretty completely,

00:43:13.420 --> 00:43:19.090
and what was a shock to
me was how wrong I had it.

00:43:19.090 --> 00:43:21.770
I thought it was the
absolute corruption,

00:43:21.770 --> 00:43:27.930
and the Kennedy library gave him
the profiles in courage award

00:43:27.930 --> 00:43:33.870
for pardoning Nixon,
and I watch that and I,

00:43:33.870 --> 00:43:37.050
it's true, it was a cold shower.

00:43:37.050 --> 00:43:42.680
And then I realized, you know,
how humbling, how, to be honest,

00:43:42.680 --> 00:43:46.850
humiliating it was, because
I was sure it was corrupt,

00:43:46.850 --> 00:43:50.460
and then you examine
it 25 years later,

00:43:50.460 --> 00:43:53.390
and it's the precise opposite.

00:43:53.390 --> 00:44:01.350
It's courage, and so that puts
a, puts you, your judgmental,

00:44:01.350 --> 00:44:05.280
the part of your head,
in slow motion.

00:44:05.280 --> 00:44:07.430
Don't rush to judgments.

00:44:07.430 --> 00:44:09.080
You may have it absolutely wrong.

00:44:09.080 --> 00:44:11.180
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: Did you
